  "plot_summary": "[ASSET: right | ComiCollector | width=29%] [HANG0] Marvel's constant barrage of letters from readers wanting to buy and sell back issues finally comes to a head in the letters page of [LINK:1963:FF_15|FF #15], where Marvel announces they can't print such requests anymore and directs fans instead to the \"mag called the <b>COMICOLLECTOR</b>, published by Ronn Foss\" (and provides his address).&nbsp; Anyone wishing to buy, sell or trade is encouraged to contact him.\n[BR]\n[BR] Interestingly enough, today you can find back issues of <b>COMICOLLECTOR</b> on sale at auctions.&nbsp; It's considered one of the earliest fanzines.&nbsp; Ronn apparently died in 2001.\n\n[HANG0] I was also impressed by the couple of pages of self-promotion on display in this month's issue of <i>Fantastic Four</i>, which featured two half-page ads promoting Ant-Man and Doctor Doom's appearance in the next issue, one that heralded the debut of <i>Sgt. Fury</i> #1, and the last listing out several FF fan clubs.&nbsp; It's the first time I've seen internal evidence of Marvel taking advantage of its own page count to self-promote.\n[BR]\n[BR] Of course, it should also be noted that these pages, the pin-up, and the two pages of letters finally reduced the actual story's page count to 20, which essentially became the new normal throughout the 1960s.&nbsp; Up until this point, the count had been around 23-24 pages.",
